The current implementation of your `Delete` function correctly updates the Node that is replacing the one being deleted (i.e., the inorder successor). However, there is a missing step for deleting a node with two children. When you replace the deleted node's data with its inorder successor's data, you also have to delete the inorder successor itself, which may have a right child.

Here is the vital part of the `Delete` function that needs some adjustment:

```cpp
// Else node with two children: Get the inorder successor (smallest
// in the right subtree)
Node* temp = minValueNode(root->right);

// Copy the inorder successor's data into this node
root->data = temp->data;

// Delete the inorder successor
root->right = Delete(root->right, temp->data);
```

You are already doing this part correctly. However, what is critical is that we properly update the parent pointer of the right child of the inorder successor, if it exists. This is correctly handled by the `Delete` function when it is recursively called on `root->right`.

The key is to ensure that the `minValueNode` function's returned node always has the correct `parent` reference for your AVL tree to work as expected, with all parent-child relationships properly maintained. It looks like your implementation does cover this because the `minValueNode` function traverses only via the `left` child, and the nodes aren't modified during that traversal, so the `parent` pointer should still be accurate.

When deleting the inorder successor, if it has a right child, it should replace the inorder successor, and its `parent` pointer will be updated accordingly in this block:

```cpp
if ((root->left == nullptr) || (root->right == nullptr)) {
  Node* temp = root->left ? root->left : root->right;
  Node* parent = root->parent;

  // Copy fields from temp to root, including left and right child pointers
  if (temp != nullptr) {
    root->left = temp->left;
    root->right = temp->right;
    root->data = temp->data;

    // Don't forget to update the parent pointers of the children
    if (root->left) root->left->parent = root;
    if (root->right) root->right->parent = root;
  } else {
    root = nullptr;
  }
  delete temp; // delete the inorder successor node properly
}
```

After the node gets deleted, and its data get replaced with that of its inorder successor, the AVL tree's balance might have been disturbed. Therefore, the tree must be rebalanced from the point of the original deletion up to the root. The current implementation is already handling this with the `UpdateHeightAndBalance` and `BalanceTree` functions called towards the end of the `Delete` function.

Your code already rebalances appropriately, and the parent pointers seem to be updated correctly within the recursive `Delete` function, with the `RightRotation` and `LeftRotation` maintaining the `parent` pointer of each involved node. So, in conclusion, as long as the functions `minValueNode`, `RightRotation`, `LeftRotation`, `UpdateHeightAndBalance`, and `BalanceTree` correctly handle the parent pointers and update the appropriate balance factors, your AVL tree should properly maintain its AVL properties, including correct child-parent links after the deletion.

