Certainly! To remove a node with two children in an AVL tree without recursion, you'll need to perform the find-and-replace operation iteratively. This generally involves locating the inorder successor iteratively and then swapping the values.

Below is a non-recursive version of the `Delete` function for removing a node with two children:

```cpp
Node* Delete(Node* root, int key) {
  Node* current = root;
  Node* toDelete = nullptr;
  Node* parent = nullptr;

  // Find node to delete
  while (current != nullptr) {
    if (key < current->data) {
      current = current->left;
    } else if (key > current->data) {
      current = current->right;
    } else {
      toDelete = current;
      break;
    }
  }

  if (toDelete == nullptr) {
    return root; // Node to delete not found
  }

  // Node with two children
  if (toDelete->left != nullptr && toDelete->right != nullptr) {
    parent = toDelete;
    Node* succ = toDelete->right; // Start with right child

    // Find inorder successor (leftmost node of right subtree)
    while (succ->left != nullptr) {
      parent = succ;
      succ = succ->left;
    }

    toDelete->data = succ->data; // Copy inorder successor's data
    toDelete = succ; // Successor will be deleted instead
  }

  // Node with zero or one child
  Node* subtree = (toDelete->left != nullptr) ? toDelete->left : toDelete->right;

  if (parent == nullptr) {
    root = subtree; // Delete root node
  } else {
    if (parent->left == toDelete) {
      parent->left = subtree;
    } else {
      parent->right = subtree;
    }
  }

  if (subtree != nullptr) {
    subtree->parent = parent;
  }

  delete toDelete;

  // Starting from the parent of the originally deleted node,
  // traverse up the tree and update heights and rebalance
  while (parent != nullptr) {
    UpdateHeightAndBalance(parent);
    parent = BalanceTree(parent);
    parent = parent->parent;
  }

  return root;
}
```
In this `Delete` implementation, we manually find the node we want to delete in a loop instead of recursion. Next, if the node has two children, we look for its inorder successor in the right subtree. Once we find the successor, we swap the values and set `toDelete` to the successor. This is because, after swapping, we will actually be removing the successor which should have a maximum of one child.

At this point, the `toDelete` node will have at most one child. We save the child (if it exists) and proceed to unlink `toDelete` from the tree while capturing the parent of `toDelete` for rebalancing. We then delete `toDelete` and rebalance the tree starting from `toDelete`'s parent up to the root.

Remember that AVL deletion involves rebalancing the tree which cannot be done without some recursion unless you use an iterative approach like a loop to go up the tree from child to parent until you reach the root, rebalancing each subtree as needed. 

The implementation above is still recursive in this aspect, it traverses up the tree, updating heights, and rebalancing along the way. However, this does avoid recursion when finding the node to delete and its inorder successor.

