For example, with `[9, 9]`, your `while` loop iterates and turns all `9`s into `0`s, then increments the digit after the last `9`. Since there's no digit after the last `9`, no increment happens, leaving you with `[0, 0]` instead of the expected `[1, 0, 0]`.

To handle edge cases where all the digits are `9` or there's a carryover beyond the first digit, we must correctly set the carry and iterate through all digits, adding the carry as necessary, and handle a digit overflow at the end if required.

Here is the corrected `plusOne` function:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> plusOne(vector<int>& digits) {
        int carry = 1;  // Initialize carry to one for the plus one operation
        std::reverse(digits.begin(), digits.end());

        for (int i = 0; i < digits.size(); ++i) {
            int sum = digits[i] + carry;
            digits[i] = sum % 10;  // Update the digit
            carry = sum / 10;  // Calculate the new carry
            if (carry == 0) {
                break;  // No need to continue if there is no carry
            }
        }

        if (carry > 0) {
            // If there's still carry left, add a new digit at the end
            digits.push_back(carry);
        }

        std::reverse(digits.begin(), digits.end());
        return digits;
    }
};
```

This solution resolves the issue by handling each digit and checking the carry from each addition, and finally by appending a new digit if there's still carry after processing the least significant digit. The sequence is reversed at the beginning and once again at the end to make it easier to iterate from the least significant digit to the most significant digit.

