To generate Gray codes without storing them in a vector, you can directly print them as you go. The pattern for Gray codes is such that the second half of the sequence is a mirror of the first half, with the addition of a '1' prefixed to each code. 

Here's the modified function that generates and prints Gray codes without using a vector:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

void PrintGrayNums(int n, int &num) {
  if (n == 0) {
    for (int i = num; i > 0; --i) {
      std::cout << ((num >> i) & 1);
    }
    std::cout << (num & 1) << '\n';
  } else {
    PrintGrayNums(n - 1, num);  // First half
    num = num ^ (1 << (n - 1)); // Toggle the n-th bit
    PrintGrayNums(n - 1, num);  // Second half, with the n-th bit toggled
  }
}

int main() {
  int n;
  std::cin >> n;
  int num = 0;  // Start with 0
  PrintGrayNums(n, num);
  return 0;
}
```

This version of `PrintGrayNums` uses recursion. It starts with the base case: when `n` is 0, it simply prints the current number `num` in binary. For each call with `n > 0`, it prints the first half of the Gray code sequence for `n - 1` bits, toggles the n-th bit, and then prints the second half. The bit toggling creates the mirror image with the leading '1's that's characteristic of Gray codes. The variable `num` is carried through each recursive call by reference, allowing for modification across the recursion levels.

This code assumes that the least significant bit is at the nth position (rightmost bit is in the 0th position) when printing, which corresponds to standard Gray code construction. Adjust the printing loop for ordering if necessary.
